# Chapter 15 — Building a game with slats

Let's build a paddle game.

You're going to write a small cart. A ball. A paddle. A score. A save
file. Every piece of it is a slat somewhere — the cart is a slat, the
save is a slat, the incident narrative the runtime writes about your
session is a slat.

By the end of this chapter, you will have a working cart. You will
have inherited it from a community cart. You will have signed your
version. You will have saved it. You will understand why the substrate
made all of that free.

## Start from a community cart

There's already a paddle game in the community. Someone your age
wrote it last week. It's `cart-community-paddle-1`. Load it.

```motoi-scheme
(load-community-cart \"cart-community-paddle-1\")
```

You get back a slat-record. That's the cart.

```motoi-scheme
(define parent (load-community-cart \"cart-community-paddle-1\"))
(slat-key parent 'body)
```

That gives you the source. It looks like this:

```motoi-scheme
(cart
  :id \"cart-community-paddle-1\"
  :author 'someone
  :ts #inst \"2026-07-04T14:00:00Z\"
  :body
    ((define ball    (make-sprite 'ball    :x 100 :y 50 :vy 5))
     (define paddle  (make-sprite 'paddle  :x 100 :y 250))

     (define (on-frame)
       (sprite-move! ball :dx 0 :dy (sprite-vy ball))
       (when (touched? ball paddle)
         (sprite-flip-vy! ball))
       (when (out-of-bounds? ball)
         (reset! ball)))

     (main-loop on-frame)))
```

Nine lines of Scheme. A ball falls. If it touches the paddle, it
bounces. If it goes off screen, it resets. That's the game.

Play it. It works. It's silly. Now let's make it yours.

## Inherit from the parent

```motoi-scheme
(define my-cart
  (list 'cart
        :id \"cart-my-paddle\"
        :author (whoami)
        :extends \"cart-community-paddle-1\"
        :ts (now)
        :body
          '((define score 0)

            (define (on-collision)
              (set! score (+ score 1))
              (display score))

            (extend on-frame on-collision))))
```

That's a cart. It doesn't include the parent's body — it EXTENDS it.
The runtime pulls the parent's slats, layers your changes over them,
runs the combined cart. Inheritance without recompilation.

The `:extends` field tells the runtime to load the parent first. Your
`on-collision` runs when the ball touches the paddle (because the
runtime knows how to compose `on-frame` and `on-collision`).

## Run the cart

```motoi-scheme
(run-cart my-cart)
```

The game runs. Now every time the paddle catches the ball, the score
goes up. You see the number climb.

You made a game. The community wrote the base. You wrote the score.
Both work.

## Save your progress

```motoi-scheme
(define save
  (list 'artifact-state
        :type 'cart-save
        :id (slat-key my-cart 'id)
        :state (list
                 (list 'score score)
                 (list 'ball-position (sprite-position ball))
                 (list 'paddle-position (sprite-position paddle)))
        :ts (now)))

(save-artifact! save)
```

The save is an `artifact-state` slat. Three fields:

- `:type` — what kind of artifact this is. `cart-save`.
- `:id` — which cart it saves. Yours.
- `:state` — the actual game state. A list of `(name value)` pairs.
- `:ts` — when it was saved.

## Sign the save

If you want to prove this save is really yours, sign it.

```motoi-scheme
(define signed-save
  (slat-sign save
             :signer (whoami)
             :key (my-private-key)))

(save-artifact! signed-save)
```

Now the save file is wrapped in a `(signed :body … :signature …)`
envelope. Anyone who loads it can verify — with your public key —
that you're the one who saved it.

Why would you want that? Because if you ship the save to a friend,
they can verify it's really from you. Because if you compete on a
leaderboard, the leaderboard operator can verify you played the score
yourself. Because if you build a cart together with a friend, each
save carries proof of who was playing.

## Load a save

Next time you open Lacuna:

```motoi-scheme
(define loaded (load-artifact \"cart-my-paddle\" :latest))
(slat-verify loaded :public-key (my-public-key))
```

You get the save back. `slat-verify` returns `#t`. Your save is
authentic.

Now restore the state:

```motoi-scheme
(define state (slat-key loaded 'state))
(set! score (cadr (assoc 'score state)))
(sprite-set-position! ball   (cadr (assoc 'ball-position state)))
(sprite-set-position! paddle (cadr (assoc 'paddle-position state)))

(run-cart my-cart)
```

The score is where you left it. The ball is where you left it. The
paddle is where you left it. The game resumes.

## the runtime remembers

While you were playing, the runtime wrote a cortex-slice about your
session:

```motoi-scheme
(cortex-read 'kid.you.paddle-game)
```

You get:

```
((cart-id \"cart-my-paddle\")
 (extends \"cart-community-paddle-1\")
 (author (whoami))
 (last-touched 12)
 (atoms-learned (score-var mutation inheritance signing))
 (notes \"made a paddle game. added a score. signed the save.\"))
```

She remembers. Next time you open the cart, she'll know where you
left off.

## The four slats behind the scenes

The whole session involved four slats.

1. **The cart itself.** A `cart` record with `:body` and `:extends`.
   Persists as `.slat` on disk. Human-readable. You can edit it in a
   text editor.

2. **The save file.** An `artifact-state` record with `:state`.
   Persists as `.slat` on disk. Signed with your key.

3. **The event log.** A `.slatl` stream of events. Every ball-paddle
   collision. Every score change. Every save. Every load. Every move.
   Streamed to Loam.

4. **The cortex slice.** A `cortex-slice` record summarizing what
   the runtime remembers about the session. Persists as `.slat` in
   `~/.cortex/motoi/`.

Every one of them is legible. Every one of them is a slat. Every one
of them can be inspected, quoted, signed, shared, restored.

## The community cart tree

Your cart `cart-my-paddle` extends `cart-community-paddle-1`. Someone
else might extend `cart-my-paddle` next week — say, adding a
two-player mode. Their cart would say `:extends \"cart-my-paddle\"`.

The community carts form a tree. Every cart has a parent (except the
roots). Every child extends the parent by adding, removing, or
replacing slats. You can trace a cart's lineage back to its earliest
ancestor.

That's the \"networked carts\" story from the walkthrough. Chapter 18
if you're curious. Appendix I here goes deep on it.

## Failing carts are visible

If your cart fails to run — a syntax error, an infinite loop, a logic
mistake — the runtime captures the failure as a slat and posts it to
the community:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-loads \"
(cart-attempt
  :cart-id \\\"cart-my-paddle\\\"
  :ts       #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
  :outcome  :failure
  :error    (unbound-variable :name 'sccore)
  :author   (whoami))\")
```

That's not shame. That's training data. A small AI reads the failing
carts and offers suggestions. Someone else's failing cart is your
teacher. Your failing cart is theirs.

The runtime might say: *\"I saw a cart-attempt fail with `:error
(unbound-variable :name 'sccore)`. Did you mean `score`? Try changing
`sccore` to `score` and re-running.\"*

## Try this

Modify your cart. Make the ball red. Or make the paddle wider. Or add
a second ball. Or make the score reset on collision instead of adding
one.

```motoi-scheme
(define my-cart-v2
  (list 'cart
        :id \"cart-my-paddle-v2\"
        :author (whoami)
        :extends \"cart-my-paddle\"
        :ts (now)
        :body
          '((sprite-set-color! ball 'red)
            (sprite-set-width! paddle 100))))
```

Run it. See the ball red. See the paddle wider. Save it. Sign it.
Your v2 exists.

## The cart rule

**A cart is a slat-record. It extends other carts by referencing them.
Saves are slats. Failures are slats. Everything the cart does with
your data becomes a slat you can read.**

That's the game-building story on the SLAT substrate. Games become
part of the community's memory. Your progress becomes portable. Your
learning becomes trainable.

## Where next

Chapter 16 — the last one. Sharing your cart with the world. Signing
your cart, publishing to the community, seeing your name on it.

